8. Undoing Changes:
8.1 Reverting commits. 
>	Git revert creates a new commit that 	reverses the change made by earlier commit.
>	Importance:
-  Commit history is preserved. 
-  Safe for shared repositories. 
-  Preferred in team projects.
>	Command: git revert <commit-hash> : safely undoes changes
>	After pushing we can perform revert.
8.2 Resetting changes.
>	git reset moves the branch pointer to a previous commit by erasing the present commit.
>	After pushing reset does not work.
>	Types of reset
1.	Soft reset: git reset --soft <commit-hash>
•	Commit removed, staging area remains same.
2.	Mixed reset(default): git reset <commit-hash>
•	Commit removed, unstages the changes
3.	Hard reset: git reset --hard <commit-hash>
•	Commit, removed, unstage changes, changes made in file removed and restored to its original state.
